Disk Forensics > [T5]: Deleted Files Analysis

(5) Windows search database

If you have used Windows before, you may have seen this before

 

 

The Windows search database, commonly known as the Search index, is an integral part of the Windows operating system. It is recommended to turn on the indexing service to expedite searches for files or folders in Windows. This database not only stores the index to speed up searches but also plays a crucial role in forensic analysis, such as in the recovery of deleted files. For example, even when a file is deleted, its record may still persist in the "Windows search database" unless the index is updated.

Beyond aiding in file recovery, the Search index also meticulously records various user interactions with files and browsers. It logs all URLs accessed via Internet Explorer and Microsoft Edge, with the exception of activities conducted in Private Browsing Mode. This aspect is particularly significant as it implies that deleted browsing histories can still leave traces in the Search index. Moreover, the Search index keeps track of file openings on a per-user basis, capturing details like file paths, access times, and the applications used. This information remains stored even if files are deleted or renamed, offering a wealth of evidence about user interactions with files. Such capabilities make the Windows search database a potent tool in forensic investigations or scenarios where verification of file access is necessary. However, the sensitivity of the data contained within underscores the need for stringent security measures to prevent unauthorized access.

The "Windows Search database" file is located at "C:\ProgramData\Microsoft\Search\Data\Applications\Windows\Windows.edb." However, in windows 11, it has been renamed to "Windows.db"

To effectively parse and explore the contents of this database, whether it's "Windows.edb" in older versions or "Windows.db" in Windows 11, the Search Index Database Reporter (SIDR) by Aon Cyber Labs is the preferred tool. SIDR, a robust command-line utility, is designed to input a directory and recursively search for the win.edb/win.db artifact. It efficiently processes these files and outputs the data in either CSV or JSON format, which can then be seamlessly integrated with Timeline Explorer for detailed navigation and analysis.

  1. System_Item Path Display: The full file path where the file or folder is located on the computer's file system.
  2. System_Computer_Name: The name of the computer where the file was accessed or modified.
  3. System_Date_Modified: The date and time when the file was last modified.
  4. System_Date_Created: The date and time when the file was created.
  5. System_Date_Accessed: The date and time when the file was last accessed.
  6. System_Size: The size of the file in bytes.
  7. System_File_Owner: The owner of the file, typically the user or system account that created the file.

 

  1. System_Search_Auto_Summary: Automatic summary or description of the file or item generated by the Windows Search system.
  2. System_Search_Gather_Time: The date and time when the file was indexed or gathered by the Windows Search service.
  3. System_Item_Type: Indicates the type of item, such as Directory, File, Link, etc.

For more details, you can check out this blog from Aon Cyber Labs, where they delve into the Windows search index artifact and the Search Index Database Reporter (SIDR) in great detail.
